04239nam a22005535i 9780674974913DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20172017mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806749749137 a10.4159/97806749749132doi  a(DE-B1597)487727  a(OCoLC)999361601  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aKF4783b.T43 2017 7aLAW0180002bisacsh04a342.7308/522231 aTebbe, Nelson, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aReligious Freedom in an Egalitarian Age /cNelson Tebbe. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (230 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tI: Method -- t1. Social Coherence -- t2. The Skeptics’ Objections -- tII: Principles -- t3. Avoiding Harm to Others -- t4. Fairness to Others -- t5. Freedom of Association -- t6. Government Nonendorsement -- tIII: Applications -- t7. Public Accommodations -- t8. Employment Discrimination -- t9. Public Officials -- t10. Government Subsidy and Support -- tAfterword -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTensions between religious freedom and equality law are newly strained in America. As lawmakers work to protect LGBT citizens and women seeking reproductive freedom, religious traditionalists assert their right to dissent from what they see as a new liberal orthodoxy. Some religious advocates are going further and expressing skepticism that egalitarianism can be defended with reasons at all. Legal experts have not offered a satisfying response—until now. Nelson Tebbe argues that these disputes, which are admittedly complex, nevertheless can be resolved without irrationality or arbitrariness. In Religious Freedom in an Egalitarian Age, he advances a method called social coherence, based on the way that people reason through moral problems in everyday life. Social coherence provides a way to reach justified conclusions in constitutional law, even in situations that pit multiple values against each other. Tebbe contends that reasons must play a role in the resolution of these conflicts, alongside interests and ideologies. Otherwise, the health of democratic constitutionalism could suffer. Applying this method to a range of real-world cases, Tebbe offers a set of powerful principles for mediating between religion and equality law, and he shows how they can lead to workable solutions in areas ranging from employment discrimination and public accommodations to government officials and public funding. While social coherence does not guarantee outcomes that will please the liberal Left, it does point the way toward reasoned, nonarbitrary solutions to the current impasse.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCivil rightsxReligious aspects. 0aCivil rightszUnited States. 0aDiscriminationxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aEquality before the lawzUnited States. 0aFreedom of religionzUnited States. 0aLawxMethodology. 0aSexual minoritiesxCivil rightsxReligious aspects. 7aLAW / Constitutional.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311054331540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674974913423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674974913.jpg  a978-3-11-054331-5  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles